previous: Gimli also holds a five-day summer film festival, during which films are shown on a screen in the lake to audiences on the beach.

The Icelandic Festival of Manitoba has been celebrated since 1890 and has been held in Gimli since 1932.[7] Several thousand tourists come each year for three days during the August long weekend. Artworks from jewellery to paintings are displayed at the art museum as well along the pier wall that extends from downtown Gimli into the lake, and traditional Icelandic dishes are offered.
